Nit: u_long definition could be architecture specific. May be we can extract out the required bytes outside and pass it here?

uint8_t byte0 = nvmeClockStatus & 0xFF;
uint8_t byte1 = (nvmeClockStatus >> 8) & 0xFF;
...

nvmeAlert. Also, a nit: you could simply do a

if(Nvme_Lvc3_Alert_line.event_read() == gpiod::line_event::FALLING_EDGE)
{
...

}

In case of false alarm, don't we have to block rest of the statements in this code block from executing?

probably do a 
if(drivePresenceStatus != currDriveStatus) {

//...execute logic

}

else {
   //log false alarm
}

This logic misses if 2 or more drives are inserted/removed simultaneously, no? This could happen considering the fact that this is a single threaded application and there could be latencies in processing the GPIO alert line.

while (tmpVar > 0)
{
   if(tmpVar & 1)
   {
       if (DrivePresenceStatus[indexDrive] == 0)
       {
           logDeviceAdded("Drive", std::to_string(indexDrive), "N/A");
       }
       else
       {
           logDeviceRemoved("Drive", std::to_string(indexDrive), "N/A");
       }
   }
   indexDrive++;
   tmpVar >>= 1;
}

If you want to initialize with 0, prefer {}
i.e.) bitset<ALL_CLOCK_BITS_DB2000> clockStatus{0};

https://github.com/isocpp/CppCoreGuidelines/blob/master/CppCoreGuidelines.md#es23-prefer-the--initializer-syntax
